Coming into CMU, I knew that I wouldn't be the smartest one there--I wasn't even the smartest person in high school. Everyone had a different background from me, and most seemed to know more than I did. It was difficult to feel good about myself and my grades when everyone was easily getting good grades while I was struggling in my classes. In the back of my mind, I knew other people were struggling, but I never knew who they were because I guess like me, they felt embarrassed and ashamed at how "dumb" they were. I understand that I'm not dumb because I wouldn't be at CMU if I was, but it's kind of hard to accept that when everyone else is succeeding and cruising through their classes.

Study: My roommate mentioned it to me so I decided to sign up.
Pre_CMU_Adjust_Difficult: When I came to CMU, for the first time in my life I was presented with seemingly infinite opportunities. This school has everything I have ever been interested in from drone projects to build18 where you can get funding to build literally any electrical device you want to cutting edge physics research. I opened more doors in the past 4 months than I have ever opened for the entirety of my life prior to coming to CMU. This is fantastic, but it is very easy to spread oneself too thin when these opportunities are so prevalent, and this is exactly what happened to me this semester. The most difficult adjustment for me to make was prioritizing what I really want to do and not bite off more than I can chew. Opportunities are plentiful at CMU, but if you don't take care of yourself and eat well, exercise and find time to have fun, you will crack under the pressure that CMU can put on you.
